{"title_page": "The Crippled Eagles", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox militant organization\n|name = The Crippled Eagles\n|logo = The Crippled Eagles.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Unofficial emblem of the Crippled Eagles\n|dates = July 1964\u20131979\n|leader = \n|attacks = \n|motives = Defence of [[Rhodesia]], participation in the [[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n|area = {{flagicon|Rhodesia|1964}} / {{flag|Rhodesia}}<br />(now {{flag|Zimbabwe}})\n|ideology = [[Anti-communism]]\n|status = Defunct}}\n'''The Crippled Eagles''' was the informal name of a group of American [[expatriate]]s that served in the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] during the [[Rhodesian Bush War]]. The name and emblem came from author [[Robin Moore]], who offered a house in [[Salisbury, Zimbabwe|Salisbury]] as a meeting place for the Americans who served in all units of the security forces, but never had their own unit.<ref name=\"rhodesia.nl\">{{cite web |year=2009 |url = http://www.rhodesia.nl/saluteth.htm|title = SALUTE THE TROOPERS|publisher = rhodesia.nl| accessdate = 2009-03-30 | last= |quote=}}</ref> The name \"Crippled Eagle\" and their badge was meant to symbolise what they considered their abandonment by the [[Federal government of the United States|US government]]. Robin Moore and Barbara Fuca tried to publish a book with the same title, but because of the political controversy the book was refused by publishers and appeared only in 1991, when it was published as ''The White Tribe''.<ref name=\"White_Tribe\">{{cite book | last = Robin Moore and Barbara Fuca| authorlink = | title = The White Tribe|edition= November 1991|pages= 522 | publisher = Affiliated Writers of America/Publishers| isbn= 978-1-879915-03-9| year = 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nOne of the reasons for many of the American citizens who joined the Crippled Eagles was the ''[[Soldier of Fortune (magazine)|Soldier of Fortune]]'' reports about both the [[Rhodesian Bush War]] and the means of entry into the [[Rhodesian Army]]. From 1976 to 1980 almost every issue contained one or more articles about the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Churchill | first1 = Ward | author-link = Ward Churchill | year = 1980 | title = U.S. Mercenaries in Southern Africa: The Recruiting Network and U.S. Policy | journal = [[Africa Today]] | volume = 27 | issue = No. 2, 2nd Qtr. | pages = 21\u201346 | jstor = 4185921 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Taulbee | first1 = J. L. | title = Soldiers of fortune: A legal leash for the dogs of war? | doi = 10.1080/07430178508405203 | journal = Defense Analysis | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u2013203 | year = 1985 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> The first issue of the magazine in 1975 actually contained two such articles, prompting some Americans to travel to Rhodesia.<ref name=\"tradoc.army.mil.045305\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tradoc.army.mil/pao/people_portraits/April%202005/045305.htm |title=Soldier of fortune: Infantry Center\u2019s Command Sgt. Maj. Mike Kelso |last=St. Amant |first=Nikki, Spc |date=29 April 2005 |website=The Bayonet |publisher=[[United States Army Training and Doctrine Command]] |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref> After 1980, their attention turned to [[Angola]], [[Soweto]] and other hotspots around the world.\n\nApproximately 300 Americans, some with previous combat experience in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]] and other [[Theater (warfare)|theatres]], others with none, volunteered to fight in the Rhodesian Security Forces during the Rhodesian Bush War as ordinary soldiers, earning a pay packet in local currency equal to that of a Rhodesian regular, under the same conditions of service.<ref name=\"moorcraft52\">{{cite book |title=The Rhodesian War: A Military History |last1=Moorcraft |first1=Paul L. |authorlink1=Paul Moorcraft |last2=McLaughlin |first2=Peter |authorlink2=Peter McLaughlin |date=April 2008 |origyear=1982 |location=Barnsley |publisher=[[Pen and Sword Books]] |isbn=978-1-84415-694-8 |page=52}}</ref> The Americans suffered seven combat fatalities and many others were wounded in combat, some maimed for life. Five served in Rhodesia's most prestigious unit, the [[Selous Scouts]].<ref>[http://www.mercenary-wars.net/biography/john-early.html A brief biography of John Early]</ref>\n\n==Members killed==\n\nDuring the course of its existence the following American citizens died in Rhodesia:<ref>{{cite book\n|title=The Saints: The Rhodesian Light Infantry\n|last=Binda\n|first=Alexandre\n|location=Johannesburg\n|publisher=30\u00b0 South Publishers\n|year=2008\n|isbn=978-1-920143-07-7\n|pages=527\u2013529}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!width=14%|Name!!Rank!!Rhodesian Force Number!!Date Killed!!Details\n|-\n|{{sortname|John Alan|Coey}}\n|Corporal\n|725702\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1975|July|19}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|[[John Alan Coey]] graduated from [[Ohio State University]] in 1972 and flew to Rhodesia the day after he graduated. He first served in the [[Rhodesian Special Air Service]] (Rhodesian SAS), and afterwards in the [[Rhodesian Light Infantry]] (RLI), in the Second Commando, with the attached Rhodesian Army Medical Corps. He was killed in action on 19 July 1975 by a gunshot wound. He was the first American out of the Crippled Eagles to die for Rhodesia. His journal, ''A Martyr Speaks'', was published in 1988, posthumously.\n|-\n|{{sortname|George William|Clarke|nolink=1}}\n|Trooper \n|728197\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1977|May|15}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Clarke was born in Canada, he came from a family of nine children. He lived in South Africa, and later in [[Southern California]], according to some sources.<ref name=\"Book_Barrel_of_a_gun-59\">Pg 59 \u2013 {{cite book | last = Gerald Horne| authorlink = Gerald Horne | title = From the Barrel of a Gun: The United States and the War against Zimbabwe, 1965\u20131980|edition= 5 December 2000|page= 400 | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press| isbn= 978-0-8078-4903-3| year = 2001 }}</ref> He was a [[Vietnam veteran]], serving in the [[United States Marine Corps]], and was decorated with the [[Purple Heart]] twice during his marine career. Prior to joining the RLI, Clarke served as a paramedic in Richmond, British Columbia, Canada ([http://www.bcehs.ca/ EHSC]). He was aged 28 when he was killed in action. He served in the RLI, in the Support Commando. He was killed on 15 May 1977 around Mtoko, in the then Tribal Trust Land, inside Rhodesia proper.\n|-\n|{{sortname|Richard L.|Biederman|nolink=1}}\n|Sergeant \n|726685\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1977|December|6}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Biederman was from [[Minnesota]], served as a sergeant in the [[Rhodesian SAS]]. Biederman was a member of the [[American Nazi Party|NSWPP]]. He died on active service on 6 December 1977, in [[Gaza Province|Gaza Province Mozambique]] from friendly fire during an SAS Patrol.<ref name=\"mazoe.com\">{{cite web |year=2007 |url = http://www.mazoe.com/ROH_A_C.html|title = RHODESIAN ROLL OF HONOUR (A-C)|publisher = mazoe.com| accessdate = 2009-03-30 | last= |quote=Biederman, Richard L., Sergeant \u2013 Special Air Service \u2013 DOAS in an accidental shooting in Mozambique \u2013 06-Dec-77}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |year=2018 |url = http://www.therhodesiansas.com/roh.php|title = Roll of Honour|publisher = Rhodesian SAS Roll of Honour| accessdate = 2019-01-27 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"Roll of Honour\">{{cite web |year=2018 |url = https://phosphorussite.wordpress.com/2017/07/19/american-national-socialists-in-rhodesias-struggle-for-racial-freedom/|title = American National Socialists in Rhodesia\u2019s Struggle for Racial Freedom|publisher = Martin Kerr |accessdate = 2019-01-27 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |year=2018 |url = https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/190633984/richard_dick_-louis-biederman|title =SGT Richard \"Dick\" Louis Biederman|publisher = find a grave| accessdate = 2019-01-27 | last= |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{sortname|Frank P.|Battaglia|nolink=1}}\n|Trooper \n|728515\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1978|March|6}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Battaglia was born in Florida, but later moved to New York. He was a [[Vietnam veteran]] having served with the [[United States Army|US Army]] [[173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team (United States)|173rd Airborne]], and was reportedly wounded twice in the [[Vietnam War]]. He also served a full contract with the [[Spanish Foreign Legion]]. He came to Rhodesia with his wife, and went to [[Rhodesian Special Air Service|C squadron SAS]] training troop. After SAS training he joined the RLI, the 3 Commando, 14 Troop. He was killed in action on 6 March 1978, around Kavalamanja in [[Zambia]] during Operation Turmoil, by a [[Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army]] machine gun. Battaglia's wife served with the [[Rhodesian Air Force]], packing parachutes. He was an avid [[poker]] player and gave some young Rhodesian soldiers poker lessons while playing for matches.<ref name=\"therli\">{{cite web|year=2009 |url=http://therli.com/C_RollofHonour_Frank.asp |title=Frank P. Battaglia |publisher=therli |accessdate=2009-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204115033/http://www.therli.com/C_RollofHonour_Frank.asp |archivedate=4 December 2008 }}</ref><ref>Wall Street Journal 30 April 1979</ref>\n|-\n|{{sortname|Joseph Patrick|Byrne|nolink=1}}\n|Trooper \n|728721\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1978|October|26}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Joseph Patrick Byrne was an Irish-American from [[Kearney, New Jersey]]. He joined the Rhodesian Army in October 1977. He was a regular in the crowd of foreign volunteers that socialised in the Monomatapa Hotel and a friend of American author Robin Moore. He joined 3 Commando, RLI on 24 March 1978 from Recruit Intake 162. He was killed in action during Operation Repulse at the age of 26, on 26 October 1978 around Middle Sabi or Lower Sabi inside in the Mutema Tribal Trust Land, in Rhodesia proper when his patrol came under fire in an area devoid of cover.<ref name=\"Book_Barrel_of_a_gun\">{{cite book | last = Gerald Horne| authorlink = | title = From the Barrel of a Gun: The United States and the War against Zimbabwe, 1965\u20131980|edition= 5 December 2000|page= 400 | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press| isbn= 978-0-8078-4903-3| year = 2001}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{sortname|Stephen Michael|Dwyer|nolink=1}}\n|Trooper \n|729803\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1979|July|16}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Stephen Michael Dwyer was from Boston, Massachusetts. He served a tour with the [[US Marine Corps]] in [[Korea]]. He joined the RLI, the 3 Commando. He was killed in action at the age of 27, while coming to the aid of fatally wounded fellow American, Hugh John McCall, on 16 July 1979 on the Buffalo Range Area, in Rhodesia proper.<ref name=\"Book_Barrel_of_a_gun\"/>\n|-\n|{{sortname|Hugh John|McCall|nolink=1}}\n|Sergeant \n|727941\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1979|July|16}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Hugh John McCall was a Vietnam veteran, having served with the [[United States Army|US Army]] [[173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team (United States)|173rd Airborne]]. He was killed in action on 16 July 1979 on the Buffalo Range Area, in Rhodesia proper. A well-known book on the [[Rhodesian Bush War]], authored by Chris Cocks is dedicated to his memory.<ref name=\"Fireforce\">{{cite book | last = Chris Cocks| authorlink = | title = Fireforce: One Man's War in the Rhodesian Light Infantry|edition= 1 July 2001|page= 296 | publisher = Covos Day| isbn= 978-1-919874-32-6}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n|title=A Martyr Speaks\n|last=Coey\n|first=John Alan\n|authorlink=John Alan Coey\n|location=Fletcher, North Carolina\n|publisher=New Puritan Library\n|edition=First\n|date=March 1988\n|isbn=978-0-932050-41-0}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Moore\n|first=Robin\n|authorlink=Robin Moore\n|title=The Crippled Eagles\n|year=1980\n|publisher=Manor Books\n|isbn=978-0-532-23366-4}}\n*{{cite book\n|title=From the Barrel of a Gun: The United States and the War against Zimbabwe, 1965\u20131980\n|last=Horne\n|first=Gerald\n|authorlink=Gerald Horne\n|location=Chapel Hill, North Carolina\n|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]]\n|date=December 2000\n|isbn=978-0-8078-4903-3\n|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.theoutnumbered.com/view/639/21787/The-Crippled-Eagles.html The Outnumbered, the Crippled Eagles] from which most of the above information is taken\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100911004039/http://www.newrhodesian.net/ Rhodesian Bush War historical research / discussion forum]\n* [http://www.rhodesia.nl/saluteth.htm Salute the Troopies]\n* [http://www.tradoc.army.mil/pao/people_portraits/April%202005/045305.htm Sgt. Maj. Mike Kelso's look-back]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crippled Eagles}}\n[[Category:Foreign volunteers in the Rhodesian Security Forces]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Rhodesia\u2013United States relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox militant organization\n|name = The Crippled Eagles\n|logo = The Crippled Eagles.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Unofficial emblem of the Crippled Eagles\n|dates = July 1964\u20131979\n|leader = \n|attacks = \n|motives = Defence of [[Rhodesia]], participation in the [[Rhodesian Bush War]]\n|area = {{flagicon|Rhodesia|1964}} / {{flag|Rhodesia}}<br />(now {{flag|Zimbabwe}})\n|ideology = [[Anti-communism]]\n|status = Defunct}}\n'''The Crippled Eagles''' was the informal name of a group of American [[expatriate]]s that served in the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] during the [[Rhodesian Bush War]]. The name and emblem came from author [[Robin Moore]], who offered a house in [[Salisbury, Zimbabwe|Salisbury]] as a meeting place for the Americans who served in all units of the security forces, but never had their own unit.<ref name=\"rhodesia.nl\">{{cite web |year=2009 |url = http://www.rhodesia.nl/saluteth.htm|title = SALUTE THE TROOPERS|publisher = rhodesia.nl| accessdate = 2009-03-30 | last= |quote=}}</ref> The name \"Crippled Eagle\" and their badge was meant to symbolise what they considered their abandonment by the [[Federal government of the United States|US government]]. Robin Moore and Barbara Fuca tried to publish a book with the same title, but because of the political controversy the book was refused by publishers and appeared only in 1991, when it was published as ''The White Tribe''.<ref name=\"White_Tribe\">{{cite book | last = Robin Moore and Barbara Fuca| authorlink = | title = The White Tribe|edition= November 1991|pages= 522 | publisher = Affiliated Writers of America/Publishers| isbn= 978-1-879915-03-9| year = 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nOne of the reasons for many of the American citizens who joined the Crippled Eagles was the ''[[Soldier of Fortune (magazine)|Soldier of Fortune]]'' reports about both the [[Rhodesian Bush War]] and the means of entry into the [[Rhodesian Army]]. From 1976 to 1980 almost every issue contained one or more articles about the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Churchill | first1 = Ward | author-link = Ward Churchill | year = 1980 | title = U.S. Mercenaries in Southern Africa: The Recruiting Network and U.S. Policy | journal = [[Africa Today]] | volume = 27 | issue = No. 2, 2nd Qtr. | pages = 21\u201346 | jstor = 4185921 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Taulbee | first1 = J. L. | title = Soldiers of fortune: A legal leash for the dogs of war? | doi = 10.1080/07430178508405203 | journal = Defense Analysis | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u2013203 | year = 1985 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref> The first issue of the magazine in 1975 actually contained two such articles, prompting some Americans to travel to Rhodesia.<ref name=\"tradoc.army.mil.045305\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tradoc.army.mil/pao/people_portraits/April%202005/045305.htm |title=Soldier of fortune: Infantry Center\u2019s Command Sgt. Maj. Mike Kelso |last=St. Amant |first=Nikki, Spc |date=29 April 2005 |website=The Bayonet |publisher=[[United States Army Training and Doctrine Command]] |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref> After 1980, their attention turned to [[Angola]], [[Soweto]] and other hotspots around the world.\n\nApproximately 300 Americans, some with previous combat experience in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]] and other [[Theater (warfare)|theatres]], others with none, volunteered to fight in the Rhodesian Security Forces during the Rhodesian Bush War as ordinary soldiers, earning a pay packet in local currency equal to that of a Rhodesian regular, under the same conditions of service.<ref name=\"moorcraft52\">{{cite book |title=The Rhodesian War: A Military History |last1=Moorcraft |first1=Paul L. |authorlink1=Paul Moorcraft |last2=McLaughlin |first2=Peter |authorlink2=Peter McLaughlin |date=April 2008 |origyear=1982  |location=Barnsley |publisher=[[Pen and Sword Books]] |isbn=978-1-84415-694-8 |page=52}}</ref> The Americans suffered seven combat fatalities and many others were wounded in combat, some maimed for life. Five served in Rhodesia's most prestigious unit, the [[Selous Scouts]].<ref>[http://www.mercenary-wars.net/biography/john-early.html A brief biography of John Early]</ref>\n\n==Members killed==\n\nDuring the course of its existence the following American citizens died in Rhodesia:<ref>{{cite book\n|title=The Saints: The Rhodesian Light Infantry\n|last=Binda\n|first=Alexandre\n|location=Johannesburg\n|publisher=30\u00b0 South Publishers\n|year=2008\n|isbn=978-1-920143-07-7\n|pages=527\u2013529}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!width=14%|Name!!Rank!!Rhodesian Force Number!!Date Killed!!Details\n|-\n|{{sortname|John Alan|Coey}}\n|Corporal\n|725702\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1975|July|19}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|[[John Alan Coey]] graduated from [[Ohio State University]] in 1972 and flew to Rhodesia the day after he graduated. He first served in the [[Rhodesian Special Air Service]] (Rhodesian SAS), and afterwards in the [[Rhodesian Light Infantry]] (RLI), in the Second Commando, with the attached Rhodesian Army Medical Corps. He was killed in action on 19 July 1975 by a gunshot wound. He was the first American out of the Crippled Eagles to die for Rhodesia. His journal, ''A Martyr Speaks'', was published in 1988, posthumously.\n|-\n|{{sortname|George William|Clarke|nolink=1}}\n|Trooper \n|728197\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1977|May|15}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Clarke was born in Canada, he came from a family of nine children. He lived in South Africa, and later in [[Southern California]], according to some sources.<ref name=\"Book_Barrel_of_a_gun-59\">Pg 59 \u2013 {{cite book | last = Gerald Horne| authorlink = Gerald Horne | title = From the Barrel of a Gun: The United States and the War against Zimbabwe, 1965\u20131980|edition= 5 December 2000|page= 400 | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press| isbn= 978-0-8078-4903-3| year = 2001 }}</ref> He was a [[Vietnam veteran]], serving in the [[United States Marine Corps]], and was decorated with the [[Purple Heart]] twice during his marine career. Prior to joining the RLI, Clarke served as a paramedic in Richmond, British Columbia, Canada ([http://www.bcehs.ca/ EHSC]). He was aged 28 when he was killed in action. He served in the RLI, in the Support Commando. He was killed on 15 May 1977 around Mtoko, in the then Tribal Trust Land, inside Rhodesia proper.\n|-\n|{{sortname|Richard L.|Biederman|nolink=1}}\n|Sergeant  \n|726685\n|{{nowrap|{{sortdate|format=dmy|1977|December|6}}}}\n|class=\"unsortable\"|Biederman was from [[Minnesota]], served as a sergeant in the [[Rhodesian SAS]]. Biederman was a member of the [[American Nazi Party|NSWPP]]. He died on active service on 6 December 1977, in [[Gaza Province|Gaza Province Mozambique]] from friendly fire during an SAS Patrol.<ref name=\"mazoe.com\"